SIMPLE: micromercurialism
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: micromercurialism
<hw>micromercurialism</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>micro</ets> +
<ets>mercurialism</ets>. Coined by the chemist <person>A. Stock</person>
in 1926. See <er>mercurialism</er>.]</ety> <fu>(1926)</fu> <def>A form
of mercury poisoning resulting from long term exposure to low doses of
mercury. The syndrome of micromercurialism involves complex symptoms of
stress, fatigue, memory loss, fine tremors, muscular and reflex
insufficiency and low blood pressure, caused by accumulation of mercury
in the system. A condition of hyperthermia is accompanied by a series of
functional changes under the effects of mercury. The combined
simultaneous effect of toxic action, temperature and galvanic response
infers a cycle of disintegration and change.</def> <au>Work With Mercury
(1972)</au> <note>As proposed by Stock, the syndrome was considered as
the union of pathological changes in human body caused by means of low
concentrations (as low as 0.01 mg per cubic meter) of mercury vapor over
long exposure times (up to 10 years).</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

